In article <3bvup1$n1c@george.inhouse.compuserve.com>,
 <pmb@csi.compuserve.com> wrote:
>Indicator of what?  There are lots of administrative features for NT that
>blow what "comes with" Unix out of the water. And there's SMS (System
>Management Server) that's now available (MS "BackOffice" server suite).
>And there's a pretty clear direction of where the platform will take us,
>with the outline of "Cairo" on the horizon, and the look of "Win95" currently
>in beta.
>
>I don't _expect_ NT to have all the exact same solutions and features as Unix.
>It's a new OS, not a twenty-year-old OS that's been hacked by grad student
>hackers for decades <G>.  It has different philosophies and paradigms, and
>though it's "target" audience largely overlaps that of the modern Unixes, it
>is NOT the same "target".  Unix is simply better for many people than NT is,
>and vice-versa.  And the "Unix" way of doing things isn't always the BEST
>way.

The question is not so much of if NT is newer, or Unix is older, or
different philosophies and paradigms. MS simply wants to get to say
what you ought to have in your OS. My bottom line is as long as MS
is unwilling to cooperate with other OS vendors to produce a common
ground, no one should vote for MS's product. It should never gain
any momentum. IMHO, democracy is the BEST process no matter NT or
Unix will be the choice. And it just so happen to be some of the Unix
users and vendors who support this type of process.

I tend to believe OS and networking should be tomorrow's utilities,
just like your water, sewer, electricity, and highways. Whoever make
OS and network should also make it on a set of standard. I know my
water pipe comes into my neiborhood at a fixed size, I don't see why
my OS should be any different.

>And as for Unix/Internet tools for NT, I think many will be released with the
>Resource Kit for Windows NT 3.5 (due shortly).  That will plug up yet another
>few perceived "holes" in functionality.

Why NT vs. Unix has to be so focused on the nit bit of the so called
functionality? NT and Unix can have the functionality to each of his
heart content, as long as each can talk to the other, in both of the
application AND developement levels of course.
