Yeah.  Look how much good it's done in some areas with Unix.  Or
should I say "The Unixes", since some Unix implementations aren't
really all that compatible with other implementations...

"Democracy" has it's uses, but it can sometimes get in the way too.
MS has a decent product here, and I'm not going to say it "shouldn't
gain any momentum" because it's a good solution, and MS (at least
in this instance) is listening and adding what users want/need.  And
faster than a gaggle of comittees ever could.  It's still a Democracy...
if you don't like MS's OS on it's own merits, don't use it and go use
something else.  I don't think it's a valid argument to not use an OS
just because it wasn't designed by comittee.

>I tend to believe OS and networking should be tomorrow's utilities,
>just like your water, sewer, electricity, and highways. Whoever make
>OS and network should also make it on a set of standard. I know my
>water pipe comes into my neiborhood at a fixed size, I don't see why
