pmb@csi.compuserve.com wrote:
: In article <D04yBH.99L@news.cern.ch> danpop@cernapo.cern.ch (Dan Pop) writes:
: >>With a 3rd party telnet program, I can run command windows and console apps
: >        ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
: >Why a 3rd party telnet program?  Isn't MS able to provide one with NT,
: >as is the case with any Unix distribution?
: >

: In case you haven't checked, NT isn't Unix.  And MS is famous (notorious?)
: for leaving lots of openings and possibilities for 3rd party developers to
: fill.  And I think it's telnetd that's missing...

and again:

: If you want graphical output right now, there are any number of 3rd party
: X clients/servers available.  And you can run X programs on NT.  Woo-woo!

Hey, this is real cool.  If we, at Novell, put a freeware feature into
our Unix product, and then don't fully support it (like sendmail), or leave
out a feature but have in on the ftp server (like Mosaic), we get knocked
by all and sundry.  If we provide something that (initially) was in need
of improvement (like the original X11R4 server), or don't implement
something because it's a security risk (like Yellow Pages in their traditional
form), we get stick.  And that's _after_ we've put in the full TCP/IP, X,
Motif and OpenLook.

Now if MS leave out just about anything they choose, it's "an opportunity
for 3rd party developers."  I'd re-phrase that as:  an opportunity to
spend much more on the OS than Bill's quoted list price.

